			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-02T05:22:12+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 2, 2014 1:22 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 2, 2014 1:22 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592 youtube-video-container">
<div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="6TiMMEFRD-E" data-start="">
<div class="thumb"><img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/6TiMMEFRD-E/0.jpg" />
<div class="playButton">
<div class="arrow"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="caption">In an interview, the architect Ruan Hao explained the reasons behind the school&#8217;s unusual design. </div>
</div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/02/with-land-scarce-chinese-school-builds-rooftop-track/" data-title="With Land Scarce, Chinese School Builds Rooftop Track" data-description="The running track atop the school building provides enough play and exercise space for 1,600 students at a time, the school&#039;s principal told Chinese radio. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t12h27s" class="update">Updated, 12:27 a.m. ET| </span>Space is at a premium in the cities of eastern China. Property prices have been surging for years. On Tuesday, the official Twitter accounts of Peopleâs Daily, Xinhua and China Central Television, all state news organizations, posted striking photographs of how one primary school in Tiantai County, Zhejiang Province, is coping with the urban squeeze.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The No. 2 Primary School, hemmed in by multistory apartment buildings, has built a 200-meter, or almost 220-yard, running track atop its roof. One photograph shows children in school uniforms dashing along the five-lane track with wide grins. Peopleâs Daily, the official newspaper of the Communist Party, lauded the project as the â1st case of its kind in China.â<br />
<span id="more-17983"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Xinhua, the official news agency, called the institution a âland-scarce primary school,â and CCTV News said the track had been built to âfix space issues.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The track was first put to use on Monday, the opening day of the new school year across China. The school principal, Qiu Tianguo, said the track would allow 1,600 students to take part in outdoor activities, according to a <a href="//english.cri.cn/12394/2014/09/01/53s842690.htm">report</a> on the website of China Radio International.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An <a href="//www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2014-09/02/content_18529444.htm">article</a> in China Daily, an official English-language newspaper, said the track provided 3,000 square meters, or just over 32,000 square feet, of play and exercise space. The design for the track was officially presented at the 14th International Architecture Exhibition at Venice this year, it said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âUnder the circumstances that limited land cannot provide enough space for students to exercise in, we chose to challenge the concept that playgrounds and tracks have to be on the ground,â Ruan Hao, the head architect of the school project and principal at LYCS Architecture, told China Daily.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The track has an outer glass wall standing 1.8 meters, or 6 feet, high as a safety measure, as well as a 1.2-meter, or 4-foot, stainless steel rail along an inner lane. Teachers watch the students, and there are surveillance cameras, Mr. Qiu said.</p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-hide-thread"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Picture: # Running track built on school roof to fix space issues. //t.co/hR0WEB6eH1</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â <a href="https://www.twitter.com/cctvnews">CCTVNEWS (@cctvnews)</a> <a href="https://www.twitter.com/cctvnews/status/506621821828218880" data-datetime="2014-09-02T01:57:09+00:00">2 Sep 14</a><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" id="platform_twitter_js" charset="utf-8"></script></p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Officials in the central government have been experimenting with policies to try to gradually cool the real estate market, and their efforts <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/14/business/china-real-estate-falls-back-to-earth.html?_r=1">appear to be working</a> this year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many economists and financial analysts say that a sudden downturn or collapse of the property market could be disastrous for the Chinese and global economies but that Chinaâs continued dependence on an investment-driven economy linked to high property values is unsustainable.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">People living in cities have been complaining for years of the rising property sales and rental costs, which fuel inflation in many other sectors. Some Communist Party officials consider the property conundrum a potential challenge to the partyâs political legitimacy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Chinese parents who move overseas cite more space, better education facilities and cleaner environments as major reasons for their departures.</p>
	</div>
